Threads Vs Process
Firstly, Program:
A program is a sequence of instructions written in a programming language
.
This code will be interpreted or compiled into binary code
.
It is loaded into memory to execute the running
.
A program can be a simple script or a group of programs called Software, which contains blocks of programs
.
Process:
A process is simply an instance of a program that is being executed
.
A program under execution or in a currently running state is called a process
.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 2: Process Structure & Memory Space
Execution Flow: A program under execution is called a process
.
Memory Segmentation: A process is divided into specific segments based on the program:
Code Segment: Contains the executable code
.
Data Segment: Stores global variables
.
Heap: Dynamic memory allocator
.
Stack: Smallest storage location used to hold temporary data, local variables, function parameters, and function calls
.
Registers: Located directly within the CPU to hold data
.
Key Characteristics:
Each process has its own separate memory space; therefore, one process cannot corrupt another
.
Examples: Applications like Chrome, VS Code, and Spotify each run as a separate process
.
A process has its own memory space, resources, and CPU state
.
Process Life Cycle States: New → Ready ↔ Running → Terminated (with a Waiting state available)
.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 3: Thread Definition & Shared Resources
Thread:
A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process
.
A process can contain multiple threads
.
Threads inside the same process share memory and resources
.
Threads allow for concurrent execution
.
Single vs. Multi-Thread Process:
In a multi-thread process, each thread has its own registers and stack
.
However, they share the code segment, data segment, and heap
.
Communication & Risk:
Shared memory space allows for efficient communication between threads
.
Warning: A single thread can potentially corrupt the entire process
.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 4: Real-world Example & Comparison
Example (Watching YouTube):
One thread loads the video
.
One thread handles the UI
.
One thread downloads data
.
Without threads, the application would freeze while performing these tasks
.
